00:17:57,368 --> 00:17:58,735
is not in Richmond.

324
00:17:58,803 --> 00:18:01,404
It's on its way
to Washington.

325
00:18:01,472 --> 00:18:04,874
Sergeant Thomas Harney,
an explosives expert

326
00:18:04,942 --> 00:18:07,443
with the Confederate
Torpedo Bureau,

327
00:18:07,511 --> 00:18:09,445
has already been
dispatched on a secret

328
00:18:09,513 --> 00:18:11,346
mission to blow up
the White House and

329
00:18:11,414 --> 00:18:13,114
Lincoln in it.

330
00:18:13,182 --> 00:18:15,616
And there is sound evidence
that John Wilkes Booth

331
00:18:15,684 --> 00:18:18,318
learns of the plot
while in New York,

332
00:18:18,386 --> 00:18:20,554
at the same time that
Abraham Lincoln is

333
00:18:20,621 --> 00:18:22,922
walking the streets
of Richmond.

334
00:18:22,990 --> 00:18:24,890
Southern Gentleman:
Sergeant Harney is with

335
00:18:24,958 --> 00:18:27,226
Colonel Mosby in
Virginia as we speak,

336
00:18:27,293 --> 00:18:29,161
seeking to infiltrate
Washington at the

337
00:18:29,229 --> 00:18:30,462
earliest convenience.

338
00:18:30,530 --> 00:18:32,330
John Wilkes Booth:
And Jefferson Davis has

339
00:18:32,398 --> 00:18:37,035
sanctioned this
harebrained incendiary scheme?

340
00:18:37,569 --> 00:18:40,037
I see.

341
00:18:40,105 --> 00:18:42,440
And it is true that
President Davis escaped

342
00:18:42,507 --> 00:18:44,074
intact from Richmond?

343
00:18:44,142 --> 00:18:45,442
Southern Gentleman: Yes.

344
00:18:45,510 --> 00:18:49,477
Thank heaven he is
safely bound for Danville.

345
00:18:49,544 --> 00:18:53,180
You seem troubled.

346
00:18:53,448 --> 00:18:55,015
John Wilkes Booth:
Troubled?

347
00:18:55,083 --> 00:18:56,717
I?

348
00:18:56,785 --> 00:18:59,519
For four years I have
lived not daring to

349
00:18:59,587 --> 00:19:02,188
express my thoughts
or sentiments,

350
00:19:02,255 --> 00:19:06,157
even in my own home,
constantly hearing every

351
00:19:06,224 --> 00:19:10,993
principle dear to my heart
denounced as treasonable.

352
00:19:11,061 --> 00:19:13,763
And I have cursed
my willful idleness,

353
00:19:13,830 --> 00:19:17,066
begun to deem
myself a coward.

354
00:19:17,134 --> 00:19:20,969
And to despise
my own existence.

355
00:19:21,037 --> 00:19:22,870
Richmond has fallen,

356
00:19:22,938 --> 00:19:25,472
in a war against
the Constitution,

357
00:19:25,540 --> 00:19:27,007
against states' rights,

358
00:19:27,075 --> 00:19:29,642
against Southern rights
and institutions.

359
00:19:29,710 --> 00:19:32,846
And a malignant tyrant,
a half-breed,

360
00:19:32,914 --> 00:19:35,649
low-mannered, country
buffoon is threatening

361
00:19:35,717 --> 00:19:39,853
to proclaim himself king.

362
00:19:41,556 --> 00:19:45,626
I should have killed
him on Inauguration Day.

363
00:19:45,693 --> 00:19:48,662
I could have.

364
00:19:49,998 --> 00:19:53,902
I was that close.

365
00:19:53,969 --> 00:19:56,070
And now, if the South
is to be aided at all

366
00:19:56,138 --> 00:19:57,672
it must be done quickly.

367
00:19:57,740 --> 00:20:00,942
And it may already
be too late.

368
00:20:01,009 --> 00:20:04,579
Troubled, gentlemen?

369
00:20:07,482 --> 00:20:10,384
When Caesar conquered
the enemies of Rome and

370
00:20:10,452 --> 00:20:12,419
the power that was
his menaced the

371
00:20:12,487 --> 00:20:18,592
liberties of the people,
Brutus arose and slew him.

372
00:20:20,095 --> 00:20:21,662
Troubled?

373
00:20:21,730 --> 00:20:23,664
Not at all.

374
00:20:23,732 --> 00:20:26,368
I stand with Brutus.

375
00:20:27,704 --> 00:20:29,338
Tom Hanks: Lincoln
might have remained

376
00:20:29,406 --> 00:20:31,073
in Virginia, on the
battlefront with

377
00:20:31,141 --> 00:20:32,708
General Grant.

378
00:20:32,776 --> 00:20:34,543
He might even have been
present to witness

379
00:20:34,611 --> 00:20:37,045
Robert E. Lee's
surrender on April 9th.

380
00:20:37,113 --> 00:20:38,447
But, as fate
would have it,

381
00:20:38,514 --> 00:20:40,449
Secretary of State
William Seward

382
00:20:40,516 --> 00:20:42,317
and his son, Frederick,

383
00:20:42,385 --> 00:20:45,687
are victims of a carriage
accident in Washington.

384
00:20:47,123 --> 00:20:48,390
<i>[door creaks].</i>

385
00:20:48,458 --> 00:20:49,725
Abraham Lincoln:
William?

386
00:20:49,792 --> 00:20:51,459
William Bell:
Mr. President.

387
00:20:51,527 --> 00:20:53,094
Frederick Seward:
Mr. Lincoln, sir.

388
00:20:53,162 --> 00:20:55,096
Abraham Lincoln:
Frederick!

389
00:20:55,164 --> 00:21:00,535
Is your father able
to tolerate a friend?

390
00:21:02,071 --> 00:21:05,641
Frederick Seward:
This way.

391
00:21:17,487 --> 00:21:20,523
Tom Hanks: Seward's jaw
is broken in two places

392
00:21:20,590 --> 00:21:22,091
and his right
arm is fractured.

393
00:21:22,159 --> 00:21:25,461
So on April 9th,
unaware of Lee's surrender,

394
00:21:25,529 --> 00:21:27,931
Lincoln returns to
Washington to visit

395
00:21:27,998 --> 00:21:30,767
his injured
Secretary of State.

396
00:21:30,834 --> 00:21:34,204
Abraham Lincoln: I think
we near the end at last.

397
00:21:34,272 --> 00:21:38,408
Richmond is back in
the arms of the Union.

398
00:21:38,476 --> 00:21:42,013
I walked her streets.

399
00:21:42,080 --> 00:21:44,515
I sat in Jeff Davis'
own chair.

400
00:21:44,583 --> 00:21:47,885
<i>[laughs]</i>

401
00:21:48,653 --> 00:21:49,821
Miss Fanny.

402
00:21:49,888 --> 00:21:50,888
Fanny Seward:
Thank you for coming,

403
00:21:50,956 --> 00:21:52,823
Mister President.

404
00:21:52,891 --> 00:21:54,391
Abraham Lincoln: How
could I stay away when

405
00:21:54,459 --> 00:21:56,393
my Secretary of State
is rendered in such

406
00:21:56,461 --> 00:21:58,162
a way as he
cannot but listen?

407
00:21:58,230 --> 00:21:59,797
<i>[laughs]</i>

408
00:21:59,865 --> 00:22:05,670
I have worked my own hand
as hard as at sawing wood,

409
00:22:05,738 --> 00:22:08,173
so many others'
hands have I shaken.

410
00:22:08,240 --> 00:22:10,275
I've been to Libby Prison.

411
00:22:10,343 --> 00:22:13,712
General Weitzel asked
me point blank how

412
00:22:13,779 --> 00:22:15,814
to treat the defeated
Confederate soldiers.

413
00:22:15,882 --> 00:22:19,484
I told him to
let them up easy.

414
00:22:26,359 --> 00:22:29,729
My old friend.

415
00:22:29,930 --> 00:22:32,865
Tom Hanks: It is
close to 10 PM when

416
00:22:32,933 --> 00:22:35,934
Secretary of War Stanton
delivers to Lincoln

417
00:22:36,002 --> 00:22:37,970
the telegram reporting
that Robert E. Lee

418
00:22:38,038 --> 00:22:40,606
has surrendered.

419
00:22:40,674 --> 00:22:42,674
The next day,
Washington City

420
00:22:42,742 --> 00:22:44,643
is in full celebration.

421
00:22:44,711 --> 00:22:46,779
A crowd gathers in front
of the White House to

422
00:22:46,846 --> 00:22:49,683
serenade Lincoln and to
call for him to speak.

423
00:22:49,751 --> 00:22:52,986
He politely promises a
speech the next night

424
00:22:53,054 --> 00:22:55,989
and requests that
the band play the

425
00:22:56,056 --> 00:22:58,658
Confederate anthem.

