borrowed
from a private.

511
00:26:35,183 --> 00:26:37,050
Abraham Lincoln:
<i>[laughs]</i>

512
00:26:37,117 --> 00:26:38,618
Robert Todd Lincoln:
It, it was great.

513
00:26:38,686 --> 00:26:44,758
Oh and here is Lee.

514
00:26:46,526 --> 00:26:48,160
Tad Lincoln:
Papa-day, let me see!

515
00:26:48,228 --> 00:26:49,495
Can I see it?

516
00:26:49,562 --> 00:26:50,629
Can I have it?

517
00:26:50,697 --> 00:26:52,231
Mary Todd Lincoln:
Wait a moment, Tad.

518
00:26:52,298 --> 00:26:53,799
Abraham Lincoln:
Now that is the face

519
00:26:53,867 --> 00:26:55,100
of a noble man.

520
00:26:55,168 --> 00:26:57,971
And brave.

521
00:26:58,038 --> 00:27:01,608
Listen to me, Robert.

522
00:27:01,676 --> 00:27:04,845
You must lay aside
your uniform.

523
00:27:05,580 --> 00:27:07,748
Return to college.

524
00:27:07,816 --> 00:27:09,383
Read law for three years.

525
00:27:09,451 --> 00:27:11,519
And at the end of that
time I hope that we will

526
00:27:11,587 --> 00:27:13,155
be able to tell
whether you will

527
00:27:13,223 --> 00:27:14,557
make a lawyer or not.

528
00:27:14,624 --> 00:27:15,958
Robert Todd Lincoln:
Yes, sir.

529
00:27:16,026 --> 00:27:18,360
And I will, sir.

530
00:27:18,428 --> 00:27:20,096
Tom Hanks:
Shortly before 11 AM,

531
00:27:20,164 --> 00:27:22,698
Lincoln sees Secretary
of War Edwin Stanton

532
00:27:22,766 --> 00:27:23,900
at the War Department.

533
00:27:23,967 --> 00:27:26,836
Abraham Lincoln:
Mr. Stanton!

534
00:27:26,904 --> 00:27:31,607
Mrs. Lincoln has invited
General and Mrs. Grant

535
00:27:31,675 --> 00:27:35,044
to join us at the
theater this evening.

536
00:27:35,112 --> 00:27:39,015
And General Grant already
hints that they will

537
00:27:39,083 --> 00:27:41,451
decline in favor of
taking a train to

538
00:27:41,519 --> 00:27:43,386
New Jersey to visit
with their children.

539
00:27:43,454 --> 00:27:46,723
I trust that you have had
no occasion to encourage

540
00:27:46,791 --> 00:27:50,227
this desertion in the
face of entertainment.

541
00:27:50,294 --> 00:27:51,828
Edwin Stanton:
Had I the occasion,

542
00:27:51,896 --> 00:27:55,532
I would have seized it.

543
00:27:55,834 --> 00:27:59,836
I am sorry, sir, but it
is a fact that rumors of

544
00:27:59,904 --> 00:28:02,806
assassination schemes
are everywhere now.

545
00:28:02,874 --> 00:28:05,408
It remains a constant
subject of concern

546
00:28:05,476 --> 00:28:07,878
between myself
and Mr. Seward,

547
00:28:07,946 --> 00:28:09,780
even in the face
of his recovery.

548
00:28:09,847 --> 00:28:11,348
Abraham Lincoln: The
doors to the White House

549
00:28:11,416 --> 00:28:14,084
stand open to
one and all,

550
00:28:14,152 --> 00:28:15,786
day and night,
Stanton.

551
00:28:15,854 --> 00:28:20,190
My life is within reach
of anyone, sane or mad.

552
00:28:20,258 --> 00:28:24,495
By the hand of a
murderer I can die but once,

553
00:28:24,562 --> 00:28:29,467
but to, to go
continually in fear,

554
00:28:29,534 --> 00:28:35,539
why that is to die over
and over and over again.

555
00:28:46,351 --> 00:28:47,912
John Wilkes Booth:
Will you be attending

556
00:28:47,953 --> 00:28:49,954
the theater tonight?

557
00:28:50,022 --> 00:28:51,689
"Aladdin" is
playing at Grover's.

558
00:28:51,756 --> 00:28:52,890
Barber: No, sir.

559
00:28:52,958 --> 00:28:54,258
I'm afraid not, sir.

560
00:28:54,326 --> 00:28:56,527
John Wilkes Booth: Pity.

561
00:28:56,595 --> 00:28:59,963
There will be some fine
acting there tonight.

562
00:29:00,031 --> 00:29:01,465
Ulysses S. Grant:
The officers could keep

563
00:29:01,532 --> 00:29:02,832
their side-arms.

564
00:29:02,900 --> 00:29:04,667
Abraham Lincoln: And
what terms did you make

565
00:29:04,734 --> 00:29:08,203
for the common soldiers?

566
00:29:12,574 --> 00:29:14,642
Ulysses S. Grant:
I told them to go

567
00:29:14,709 --> 00:29:17,344
back to their
homes and families

568
00:29:17,412 --> 00:29:20,514
with a promise to not
again take up arms

569
00:29:20,581 --> 00:29:22,749
against the United
States of America.

570
00:29:22,816 --> 00:29:24,517
Abraham Lincoln:
Quite simple.

571
00:29:24,584 --> 00:29:26,485
And quite right.

572
00:29:26,553 --> 00:29:29,187
Which brings to mind how
very providential it is

573
00:29:29,255 --> 00:29:31,322
that this rebellion
was crushed just as

574
00:29:31,390 --> 00:29:34,891
Congress has adjourned.

575
00:29:35,092 --> 00:29:37,827
There are men in Congress
who harbor feelings of

576
00:29:37,895 --> 00:29:42,064
hate and vindictiveness
toward the South.

577
00:29:42,132 --> 00:29:46,635
But there will be no
persecution when this

578
00:29:46,703 --> 00:29:47,870
war is over.

579
00:29:47,937 --> 00:29:49,438
No bloody work.

580
00:29:49,505 --> 00:29:53,743
We must bend every effort
to reanimate the South,

581
00:29:53,810 --> 00:29:56,111
to put her state
governments in order

582
00:29:56,179 --> 00:29:57,980
and to reestablish
the Union before

583
00:29:58,048 --> 00:30:01,817
Congress reconvenes.

584
00:30:02,585 --> 00:30:05,754
Still no word from
General Sherman?

585
00:30:05,822 --> 00:30:08,957
Ulysses S. Grant: We
are hourly expecting it.

586
00:30:09,025 --> 00:30:11,093
Abraham Lincoln: It
will be good news.

587
00:30:11,160 --> 00:30:13,795
General Sherman
will have secured

588
00:30:13,863 --> 00:30:15,764
Johnston's surrender.

589
00:30:15,832 --> 00:30:19,134
I, I know this
because I have had

590
00:30:19,202 --> 00:30:22,705
the dream last night.

591
00:30:23,440 --> 00:30:25,241
I've had it before.

592
00:30:25,308 --> 00:30:27,243
It's always
the same and

593
00:30:27,311 --> 00:30:30,947
invariably followed
by favorable news.

594
00:30:31,748 --> 00:30:33,182
As Secretary
of the Navy,

595
00:30:33,250 --> 00:30:34,784
it has to do with
your element,

596
00:30:34,852 --> 00:30:36,119
Mr. Welles.

597
00:30:36,186 --> 00:30:37,653
Water.

598
00:30:37,721 --> 00:30:42,491
I am in some
kind of vessel,

599
00:30:42,692 --> 00:30:45,094
in the dream.

600
00:30:45,161 --> 00:30:49,164
And always moving
with rapidity toward

601
00:30:49,232 --> 00:30:52,768
an indefinite shore.

602
00:30:52,836 --> 00:30:55,504
Tom Hanks: In an aside,
General Grant informs the

603
00:30:55,572 --> 00:30:58,073
president that his wife
insists upon them leaving

604
00:30:58,141 --> 00:30:59,475
on the afternoon train.

605
00:30:59,542 --> 00:31:02,477
They will not be
attending the theater.

606
00:31:02,545 --> 00:31:06,181
Shortly before noon,
John Wilkes Booth stops

607
00:31:06,249 --> 00:31:08,517
at Ford's Theater,
as is his daily custom,

608
00:31:08,584 --> 00:31:09,985
to pick up his mail.

609
00:31:10,052 --> 00:31:11,252
Harry Ford: Well,
here's the man who

610
00:31:11,320 --> 00:31:12,454
don't like General Lee.

611
00:31:12,521 --> 00:31:13,688
Here for his mail.

612
00:31:13,756 --> 00:31:15,290
John Wilkes Booth:
I told you, Harry,

613
00:31:15,358 --> 00:31:16,792
I don't like the
way he surrendered.

614
00:31:16,860 --> 00:31:18,761
Given his sword by
the Senate in Richmond

615
00:31:18,829 --> 00:31:20,897
and swearing an oath
never to give it up,

616
00:31:20,964 --> 00:31:22,799
he should have died on
the battlefield before

617
00:31:22,867 --> 00:31:25,068
rendering his
Southern manhood

618
00:31:25,136 --> 00:31:26,536
to the butcher, Grant.

619
00:31:26,604 --> 00:31:27,971
<i>[chuckles].</i>

620
00:31:28,039 --> 00:31:30,741
That's what I said, Harry
and it's what I meant.

621
00:31:30,808 --> 00:31:32,876
Now let's just hope he's
not paraded through the

622
00:31:32,944 --> 00:31:35,913
streets as the Romans
did their captives, huh?

623
00:31:35,980 --> 00:31:37,414
Thank you, Raybold.

624
00:31:37,482 --> 00:31:38,949
Harry Ford: Well, I'll
be sure to ask the

625
00:31:39,017 --> 00:31:40,338
President his plan
in that regard.

626
00:31:40,352 --> 00:31:41,485
John Wilkes Booth:
The President?

627
00:31:41,553 --> 00:31:43,487
You mean the buffoon who
walked into Jeff Davis'

628
00:31:43,555 --> 00:31:46,556
house in Richmond, threw
his legs over the chair

629
00:31:46,624 --> 00:31:48,792
and spit tobacco juice
all over the place?

630
00:31:48,860 --> 00:31:51,628
<i>[men laughing].</i>

631
00:31:51,696 --> 00:31:53,163
Harry Ford: He
don't chew tobacco,

632
00:31:53,231 --> 00:31:55,432
John or I woulda put
a spittoon in the

633
00:31:55,500 --> 00:31:57,167
Presidential
Box tonight.

634
00:31:57,235 --> 00:31:58,903
A messenger for Mr.
Lincoln called this

635
00:31:58,971 --> 00:32:00,304
morning for tickets.

636
00:32:00,372 --> 00:32:02,873
For them and General
and Mrs. Grant.

637
00:32:02,941 --> 00:32:04,208
Maybe we'll have
Robert E. Lee

638
00:32:04,276 --> 00:32:05,743
and old Jefferson
Davis himself in

639
00:32:05,811 --> 00:32:08,413
another box, both
of them in chains.

640
00:32:08,481 --> 00:32:09,581
John Wilkes Booth:
I thought he was

641
00:32:09,649 --> 00:32:13,051
attending
Grover's tonight.

642
00:32:26,733 --> 00:32:33,105
<i>[singing "Honor</i>
<i>to Our Soldiers"].</i>

643
00:32:48,152 --> 00:32:51,255
Tom Hanks: Booth goes
to Pumphrey's stable

644
00:32:51,323 --> 00:32:53,958
to reserve a horse,
then to write a letter,

645
00:32:54,026 --> 00:32:55,893
a confession,
an explanation,

646
00:32:55,960 --> 00:32:57,228
a manifesto,

647
00:32:57,296 --> 00:32:59,429
signed by him on
behalf of himself,

648
00:32:59,496 --> 00:33:02,567
Lewis Powell, David Herold
and George Atzerodt.

649
00:33:02,635 --> 00:33:04,436
Meanwhile, Mr. and
Mrs. Lincoln take a

650
00:33:04,504 --> 00:33:06,537
carriage ride, alone.

651
00:33:06,605 --> 00:33:07,972
According to
Mary Todd Lincoln,

652
00:33:08,040 --> 00:33:09,640
she has never
seen her husband so

653
00:33:09,708 --> 00:33:11,175
supremely cheerful.

654
00:33:11,242 --> 00:33:13,076
They talk about
the past,

655
00:33:13,144 --> 00:33:14,444
about the death
of their son,

656
00:33:14,512 --> 00:33:16,346
Willie, three
years before,

657
00:33:16,413 --> 00:33:17,814
about the future,

658
00:33:17,881 --> 00:33:20,049
traveling abroad and
Lincoln's plan to

659
00:33:20,117 --> 00:33:22,584
return to his
law practice.

660
00:33:22,652 --> 00:33:25,286
Lincoln tells Mary that
on this particular day

661
00:33:25,354 --> 00:33:29,757
he feels that the war
has come to a close.

662
00:33:29,958 --> 00:33:31,559
They end up at the
Washington Navy Yard,

663
00:33:31,627 --> 00:33:33,394
where Lincoln summons
a young naval officer,

664
00:33:33,462 --> 00:33:35,729
William H. Flood.

665
00:33:35,797 --> 00:33:36,997
William H. Flood:
Mrs. Lincoln.

666
00:33:37,065 --> 00:33:38,665
Abraham Lincoln: Mother,
the last time we saw

667
00:33:38,733 --> 00:33:40,967
young Flood here, we
were in Springfield.

668
00:33:41,034 --> 00:33:43,335
I was a lawyer and
he was but knee-high

669
00:33:43,403 --> 00:33:44,737
to a grasshopper.

670
00:33:44,804 --> 00:33:48,039
His mother was kin
with Governor Carlin.

671
00:33:48,107 --> 00:33:49,907
Mary Todd Lincoln: Oh, I
remember Priscilla Flood.

672
00:33:49,975 --> 00:33:52,976
Abraham Lincoln: And his
father served with me

673
00:33:53,044 --> 00:33:55,478
in the Illinois
State Legislature.

674
00:33:55,546 --> 00:33:59,014
A Democrat, but, uh, a
friend and a good man,

675
00:33:59,082 --> 00:34:02,417
despite his fervent
support of my opponent

676
00:34:02,485 --> 00:34:04,152
for the presidency.

677
00:34:04,220 --> 00:34:06,655
William H. Flood:
Sins of the father, sir.

678
00:34:06,722 --> 00:34:08,283
Abraham Lincoln:
Never a sin to stand up

679
00:34:08,291 --> 00:34:09,591
for what you believe.

680
00:34:09,659 --> 00:34:12,127
Now, Flood, tell me,
which is the vessel

681
00:34:12,195 --> 00:34:13,495
with the history?

682
00:34:13,563 --> 00:34:16,198
William H. Flood:
Well, Mr. Lincoln,

683
00:34:16,266 --> 00:34:17,700
they've all been
mussing around

684
00:34:17,768 --> 00:34:19,202
under fire quite a lot,

685
00:34:19,269 --> 00:34:22,605
but I guess you mean
the Montauk over there.

686
00:34:22,673 --> 00:34:24,174
She's got the
hardest hitting.

687
00:34:24,241 --> 00:34:26,610
Been in the
tightest spots.

688
00:34:26,677 --> 00:34:27,777
Abraham Lincoln:
The very one, Flood.

689
00:34:27,845 --> 00:34:29,212
Show her to me.

690
00:34:29,280 --> 00:34:32,015
Mother?

691
00:34:41,026 --> 00:34:43,127
Tom Hanks: At 4:30, a
group of Confederate

692
00:34:43,194 --> 00:34:45,262
prisoners of war is
being escorted from the

693
00:34:45,330 --> 00:34:47,832
Navy Yard and up
Pennsylvania Avenue

694
00:34:47,899 --> 00:34:49,833
when Booth encounters
his friend,

695
00:34:49,901 --> 00:34:53,136
the actor John Mathews.

696
00:35:03,448 --> 00:35:04,748
John Wilkes Booth:
Great God,

697
00:35:04,816 --> 00:35:07,350
I have no longer
a country!

698
00:35:07,418 --> 00:35:08,652
John Mathews: What's
the matter, John?

699
00:35:08,719 --> 00:35:10,153
John Wilkes Booth:
Mathews,

700
00:35:10,221 --> 00:35:11,455
I have a favor to ask you.

701
00:35:11,522 --> 00:35:13,223
Will you grant it?

702
00:35:13,290 --> 00:35:15,258
I may have to leave
town tonight and

703
00:35:15,325 --> 00:35:16,392
I have a letter here,

704
00:35:16,460 --> 00:35:17,827
which I desire to
be published in

705
00:35:17,895 --> 00:35:19,863
the National
Intelligencer.

706
00:35:19,931 --> 00:35:21,398
Please attend to it for
me unless I see you

707
00:35:21,465 --> 00:35:25,234
before 10 o'clock tomorrow.

708
00:35:25,569 --> 00:35:27,370
John Mathews: Why, there
goes General Grant.

709
00:35:27,438 --> 00:35:28,705
John Wilkes Booth: Where?

710
00:35:28,772 --> 00:35:30,006
Come on!

711
00:35:30,074 --> 00:35:31,908
Tom Hanks: General and
Mrs. Grant will later

712
00:35:31,976 --> 00:35:33,510
recall the horseman
who peered into their

713
00:35:33,577 --> 00:35:36,479
carriage twice on its way
to the train station.

714
00:35:36,547 --> 00:35:38,682
The actor John Mathews
will be on stage

715
00:35:38,749 --> 00:35:41,585
that evening at
Ford's Theater.

716
00:35:41,652 --> 00:35:44,521
The next day he will
burn the letter.

717
00:35:44,589 --> 00:35:46,356
The signed confession
given to him by

718
00:35:46,424 --> 00:35:49,024
John Wilkes Booth.

719
00:35:49,091 --> 00:35:52,260
Abraham Lincoln has
less than 15 hours to live.

720
00:36:02,801 --> 00:36:04,102
<i>[audience laughter].</i>

721
00:36:04,170 --> 00:36:06,070
Lord Dundreary: You see,
I gave her a draught

722
00:36:06,138 --> 00:36:07,305
that cured the
effect of the draught.

723
00:36:07,373 --> 00:36:08,840
And that draught was a
draft that didn't pay

724
00:36:08,908 --> 00:36:10,242
the doctor's bill.

725
00:36:10,309 --> 00:36:11,409
Florence Trenchard:
Good gracious!

726
00:36:11,477 --> 00:36:13,378
What a number
of draughts.

727
00:36:13,446 --> 00:36:14,646
Florence Trenchard:
You have almost a

728
00:36:14,714 --> 00:36:16,181
game of draughts.

729
00:36:16,249 --> 00:36:17,483
<i>[audience laughter].</i>

730
00:36:17,550 --> 00:36:18,918
Florence Trenchard:
What's the matter?

731
00:36:18,985 --> 00:36:20,389
Lord Dundreary: That
was a joke, that was.

732
00:36:20,456 --> 00:36:21,723
Florence Trenchard:
Where's the joke?

733
00:36:21,791 --> 00:36:23,091
Lord Dundreary:
She don't see it.

734
00:36:23,159 --> 00:36:24,726
<i>[audience laughter].</i>

735
00:36:24,794 --> 00:36:28,664
Florence Trenchard: Why,
anybody can see that.

736
00:36:32,835 --> 00:36:37,572
<i>[audience applauding].</i>

737
00:36:39,142 --> 00:36:47,716
<i>[orchestra plays</i>
<i>"Hail to the Chief"].</i>

738
00:36:55,392 --> 00:37:01,397
<i>[applause continues].</i>

739
00:37:07,738 --> 00:37:09,572
Tom Hanks: At
roughly 8:30 PM,

740
00:37:09,640 --> 00:37:12,075
the Lincolns arrive
at Ford's Theater,

741
00:37:12,142 --> 00:37:14,009
driven by coachman
Francis Burke and

742
00:37:14,077 --> 00:37:15,845
footman Charles Forbes.

743
00:37:15,913 --> 00:37:18,715
Abraham Lincoln:
Mr. Forbes, Mr. Parker,

744
00:37:18,783 --> 00:37:20,917
I hope that you both
might enjoy the play.

745
00:37:20,985 --> 00:37:23,787
Tom Hanks: Since
November of 1864,

746
00:37:23,854 --> 00:37:26,356
four officers of the
Metropolitan Police

747
00:37:26,423 --> 00:37:29,826
have been detailed to
protect the President.

748
00:37:29,894 --> 00:37:34,030
On this night,
John Parker is on duty.

749
00:37:35,032 --> 00:37:37,167
As last-minute
replacements for

750
00:37:37,235 --> 00:37:39,169
General and Mrs. Grant,
Mrs. Lincoln invites her

751
00:37:39,237 --> 00:37:41,271
dear friend,
Clara Harris,

752
00:37:41,339 --> 00:37:42,673
in the company
of her fiancé,

753
00:37:42,741 --> 00:37:46,877
Major Henry
Reed Rathbone.

754
00:37:47,178 --> 00:37:51,645
<i>[audience applause].</i>

755
00:37:51,913 --> 00:37:54,247
Tom Hanks: The famously
self-educated Lincoln

